@node WHATIS "WindChime: What is it?"
WindChime is a small program that makes your Amiga sound like a wind chime. If you
listen carefully, you will also hear the sound of running water in the background.

Sounds silly? Well, just run it and see if your work rate improves, your stress
level falls or you sleep better at night.

Your mileage may vary.
@endnode

@node ABOUT "WindChime: About it."
WindChime is written in `C' (Source included) and uses EasySound written by
Anders Bjerin of the Amiga C Club.

The following disclaimer is attributed to the EasySound documentation:-

@{i}EASY-SOUND was written by Anders Bjerin, and is distributed as
public domain with NO RIGHTS RESERVED. That means that you can do
what ever you want with the program. You may use EASY-SOUND in your
own programs, commercial or not, and do not even need to mention
that you have used it. You may alter the source code to fit your
needs, and you may spread it to anyone.@{ui}

For further information about EasySound, I suggest you contact the author:-

			Anders Bjerin
			AMIGA C CLUB (ACC)
			Tulevagen 22
			181 41  LIDINGO
			SWEDEN

WindChime was compiled using Lattice C V5.0 (Yep, I still use a version
that old.) with Kickstart 1.3 headers, includes and object files. As
a consequence, WindChime @{b}should@{ub} run on any Amiga with sufficient
memory. (Reducing the size of the samples ("Chime" and "Water" specifically)
may help on machines with only 512K of chip RAM.)

WindChime has been tested on the following:-
	Original Commodore A1200, Viper '030/50Mhz, 16Mb FastRAM, Kickstart
	39.106, Workbench 40.42, various patches and a hard drive. Your
	mileage may vary....
Also:-
	Vanilla Commodore A600, 1Mb ChipRAM, Kickstart 37.300, Workbench
	37.71, various other patches and a miniscule hard drive. Again,
	your mileage may vary.

This program will work on floppy based systems.

AFAIK, this program is @{b}very@{ub} resource friendly. It's house trained,
cleans up after it's self and only consumes just a little bit too much CPU
time. I don't know how to reduce this further and probably using the Delay()
statement is not entirely the best solution given all the IDCMP messages
flying round your average system.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} As an aside, when I obtained my A600 second hand, it didn't
come with a hard drive. I obtained a small one and on fitting it, the
machine refused to see it. After poking about a bit, I discovered that the
Kickstart ROM was version 2-05 37.299, ©1992. I obtained another Kickstart
ROM, V2-05 V37.300, ©1991 and the hard drive worked. I guess this shows
another Commodore wierdness in that they were still manufacturing and
fitting old ROMs into machines with IDE interfaces, but no hard drives.
@endnode

